  <!-- AI-Optimized Summary (30-50 words) -->
  <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6 not-prose">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies industrial disc stack oil centrifuges for separating water, solids, and emulsions from petroleum and synthetic oils. Operating at up to 10,000 Gs with separation to 1 micron, capacities range from 1 to 300+ GPM. Based in Warren, Michigan with 40+ years of experience.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Working Principle -->
  <h2 id="working-principle">Working Principle</h2>

  <div class="not-prose grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start my-6">
    <div>
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
        An oil centrifuge works on the principle of differential settling using a high centrifugal force to separate oil from solid and liquid contaminants. The centrifuge exerts up to <strong>10,000 Gs of force</strong> to separate particles as small as <strong>1 micron</strong> from the oil. It also separates any immiscible liquid contaminants from the oil.
      </p>
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">
        The high-speed rotation of the bowl creates an intense centrifugal field that accelerates the natural settling process by thousands of times. Heavier particles such as metal fines, carbon residue, and other solid contaminants are forced outward against the bowl wall, while the lighter clean oil moves toward the center of the bowl and exits the centrifuge.
      </p>
    </div>
    <figure class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-md">
      <img
        src="/images/oil-centrifuge/Oil-Centrifuge-Interior-Details.webp"
        alt="Oil Centrifuge Interior Details — disc stack cross-section diagram showing bowl, disc stack, and separation chambers"
        width="600"
        height="450"
        loading="lazy"
        class="w-full"
      />
      <figcaption class="text-center text-sm text-text-muted py-2 bg-light-bg">Oil Centrifuge Section Diagram</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    When water is present, it forms an intermediate layer between the solids and the clean oil due to its density being higher than oil but lower than the solid contaminants. This three-phase separation happens continuously as the oil flows through the centrifuge, allowing for uninterrupted processing of large volumes of oil.
  </p>

  <!-- Benefits -->
  <h2 id="benefits">Benefits (Advantages)</h2>

  <p>
    An oil centrifuge offers several advantages over conventional filters and settling methods of separation. The following is a list of the essential advantages of these centrifugal separators.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-6">
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">High Separation Efficiency</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">With a centrifugal force above 7,000 Gs, the oil centrifuge can separate small particles (0.5 microns) and all free water in a single pass.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Three-Phase Separation</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">Oil centrifuges are three-phase separators that separate water and sediment simultaneously in a single continuous pass.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Compact Size</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">Oil centrifuges are relatively small for the capacity of oil they can process, fitting easily into existing plant layouts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Low Operating Cost</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">Unlike filters, centrifuges do not need filter media and the related labor and material cost, resulting in considerable savings.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Emulsion Separation</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">An oil centrifuge can break simple oil-in-water or water-in-oil emulsions. Chemically bonded emulsions need demulsifying chemicals.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Consistent Capacity</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm leading-relaxed">Unlike filters whose flow diminishes as pores get blocked, a centrifuge capacity is consistent due to its mechanical separation principle.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Drawbacks -->
  <h2 id="drawbacks">Drawbacks (Disadvantages)</h2>

  <p>
    Like all industrial equipment, centrifuges also have certain disadvantages, which are listed below.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Capital Expense:</strong> Compared to filters, centrifuges have a higher initial cost that pays off quickly due to lower operating costs.</li>
    <li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Centrifuges are mechanical machines that consist of moving parts and are subject to wear and tear. Routine maintenance is a part of centrifuge ownership.</li>
    <li><strong>Noise and Vibration:</strong> Though oil centrifuges are relatively quiet during operation, they still generate noise and vibrations due to the rotation of the bowl.</li>
    <li><strong>Skilled Operator:</strong> Centrifuges need a trained operator to operate and service them. Filtration systems are less reliant on operators.</li>
    <li><strong>Auxiliary Systems:</strong> Oil centrifuges with self-cleaning mechanisms require additional auxiliary equipment, such as water harnesses, to operate the sludge discharge mechanism.</li>
    <li><strong>Utilities:</strong> Oil centrifuges need power and other utilities to operate. Filters are static separators that do not require utilities.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Mid-page CTA -->
